{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ψευδής</b>, ές <br /> (the <i>neuter</i> <i>singular</i> ψευδές is not found in early writers, ψεῦδος being used instead, compare ψεῦδος 111; it is found in later Gr., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 669.54 (Egypt, 1st c.AD), 4th c.AD: Palaephatus Paradoxographus 6, +others, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 18(2).782); _genitive_ _sing._ ψευδοῦς [prev. author] 15.168 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; old <i>Attic dialect</i> <i>accusative</i> <i>plural</i> ψευδᾶς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 12.700 \">Refs</a>]: (ψεύδομαι):— <b>lying, false, untrue,</b> of things, opposed to ἀληθής, ψ. λόγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 229; μῦθοι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 685, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1288 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τρέπεσθαι ἐπὶ ψευδέα ὁδόν to betake oneself to <b>false</b>hood, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.117 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ψ. κατηγορία, αἰτίαι, <b>false</b> charges, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 2.183, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 15.138, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 5.41.3; λόγοι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 526; λόγος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 240e, “Cra.” 385b: ψ. λόγοι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] are also <b>fallacies,</b> in Logic, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Topica” 162b3ff \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἥδε ἡ ψ. οὐσία this <b>unreal</b> Being (i.e. the world of sense), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Plotinus Philosophus 5.8.9 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]: irregular <i>superlative</i> ψευδίστατος, εἴδη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “Varia Historia” 14.37. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of persons, <b>lying, false,</b> and as <i>substantive</i>, <b>liar,</b> οὐ γὰρ ἐπὶ ψευδέσσι πατὴρ Ζεὺς ἔσσετ᾽ ἀρωγός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.235 (only here in 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; perhaps ψεύδεσσι from ψεῦδος[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" is the true accent; so Hermappias cited in Hdn.Gr. 2.45 against 3rd-2nd c.BC: Aristarchus Grammaticus and Ptol.Asc. [prev. passage]); τοὺς θεοὺς ψευδεῖς τίθης 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 992, compare “Ant.” 657; ψ. ἔφυς 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1608 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ψ. φανήσεσθαι to be detected <b>in falsehood,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.27, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 148b; Κριτίαν ψευδῆ ἐπιδείξω [prev. author] “Chrm.” 158d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: irregular <i>superlative</i> ψευδίστατος <b>arrant liar,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" EM 110.29, compare 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 1441.25. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> τὰ ψευδῆ <b>falsehoods, lies,</b> οὐ ψευδῆ λέγω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 625, compare 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.10, etc.; οὐκ ἔσθ᾽ ὅπως λέξαιμι τὰ ψευδῆ καλά 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 620; τινὰς ψ. διαβάλλειν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 64; ψευδῶν συγκολλητής [prev. author] “Nu.” 446 (_anapaest meter_). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> ψευδέων ἀγορή, in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιδημίαι” 3.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. ή, ιβ, said to be a name of <b>the monkey-market,</b> perhaps as being <b>villanous counterfeits of humanity.</b> <br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>passive</i>, <b>beguiled, deceived,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 852. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>adverb</i> ψ